I&#39;m pretty sure this is because Spring Boot 2 is not using the required Maven Surefire plugin version for JUnit 5. Try with:

       &lt;plugin&gt;
         &lt;groupId&gt;org.apache.maven.plugins&lt;/groupId&gt;
         &lt;artifactId&gt;maven-surefire-plugin&lt;/artifactId&gt;
         &lt;version&gt;2.22.1&lt;/version&gt;
       &lt;/plugin&gt;

JUnit5 support was added in 2.22.0, see https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/SUREFIRE-1330

So, what works for Junit 5 with Spring Boot 2 is the following 3 TOGETHER:

	&lt;dependency&gt;
		&lt;groupId&gt;org.junit.jupiter&lt;/groupId&gt;
		&lt;artifactId&gt;junit-jupiter-engine&lt;/artifactId&gt;
		&lt;version&gt;5.3.1&lt;/version&gt;
		&lt;scope&gt;test&lt;/scope&gt;
	&lt;/dependency&gt;
	&lt;dependency&gt;
		&lt;groupId&gt;org.junit.jupiter&lt;/groupId&gt;
		&lt;artifactId&gt;junit-jupiter-api&lt;/artifactId&gt;
		&lt;version&gt;5.3.1&lt;/version&gt;
		&lt;scope&gt;test&lt;/scope&gt;
	&lt;/dependency&gt;
	&lt;dependency&gt;
		&lt;groupId&gt;org.junit.jupiter&lt;/groupId&gt;
		&lt;artifactId&gt;junit-jupiter-params&lt;/artifactId&gt;
		&lt;version&gt;5.3.1&lt;/version&gt;
		&lt;scope&gt;test&lt;/scope&gt;
	&lt;/dependency&gt;

Tested and verified with empty project.

Please note that @[Michael Legart&#39;s][1] answer suggesting to add 

    &lt;plugin&gt;
      &lt;groupId&gt;org.apache.maven.plugins&lt;/groupId&gt;
      &lt;artifactId&gt;maven-surefire-plugin&lt;/artifactId&gt;
      &lt;version&gt;2.22.1&lt;/version&gt;
    &lt;/plugin&gt;

Is needed for maven test (and Jenkins) to detect and execute the tests!


  [1]: https://stackoverflow.com/a/53208817/373091

What worked for me.

Don&#39;t use the version yourself add `junit-bom` 


	&lt;dependencyManagement&gt;
		&lt;dependencies&gt;
			&lt;dependency&gt;
				&lt;groupId&gt;org.junit&lt;/groupId&gt;
				&lt;artifactId&gt;junit-bom&lt;/artifactId&gt;
				&lt;version&gt;5.6.1&lt;/version&gt;
				&lt;scope&gt;import&lt;/scope&gt;
				&lt;type&gt;pom&lt;/type&gt;
			&lt;/dependency&gt;
		&lt;/dependencies&gt;
	&lt;/dependencyManagement&gt;

	&lt;dependencies&gt;
		&lt;dependency&gt;
			&lt;groupId&gt;org.junit.jupiter&lt;/groupId&gt;
			&lt;artifactId&gt;junit-jupiter-engine&lt;/artifactId&gt;
			&lt;scope&gt;test&lt;/scope&gt;
		&lt;/dependency&gt;
		&lt;dependency&gt;
			&lt;groupId&gt;org.junit.jupiter&lt;/groupId&gt;
			&lt;artifactId&gt;junit-jupiter-api&lt;/artifactId&gt;
			&lt;scope&gt;test&lt;/scope&gt;
		&lt;/dependency&gt;

Also with `maven-surefire-plugin` don&#39;t add the version

	

    &lt;build&gt;
    		&lt;plugins&gt;
    			&lt;plugin&gt;
    				&lt;groupId&gt;org.springframework.boot&lt;/groupId&gt;
    				&lt;artifactId&gt;spring-boot-maven-plugin&lt;/artifactId&gt;
    			&lt;/plugin&gt;
    			&lt;plugin&gt;
    				&lt;artifactId&gt;maven-surefire-plugin&lt;/artifactId&gt;
    			&lt;/plugin&gt;
    		&lt;/plugins&gt;
    	&lt;/build&gt;

If you write your tests in interfaces or abstract classes, _e.g._

    public interface FooTests() {

      @Test
      default void fooTest() {
        ...
      }
    }

which then get implemented by a &quot;real&quot; tester class,

    public class Tester() implements FooTests, BarTests {
      ...
    }

then what might be happening is that you ran one of those tests for the first time by itself, causing IntelliJ to remember its run configuration thereafter as `FooTests::fooTest` when really it needs to be `Tester::fooTest`. You can override this by modifying the test&#39;s run configuration, _e.g._

[![enter image description here][1]][1]

You want to replace the _Method:_ class with your non-interface, non-abstract test runner class.

  [1]: https://i.stack.imgur.com/BVgcN.png

